# speckit Specification: richards_sudoku (Python + PyQt6)

## Objective
Deliver a cross-platform PyQt6 desktop app (Python 3.13) to create, play, solve, and share multiple Sudoku variants (Standard 9x9, Jigsaw, Str8ts, Killer, 1–25). Provide robust persistence, assistance tools, statistics, and deterministic generation/solving within defined performance budgets.

## Scope
- In-scope: UI (PyQt6), puzzle generation/validation/solving, variant management (Standard, Jigsaw, Str8ts, Killer, 1–25, Codewords, KenKen, Kakuro), save/load/import/export (JSON/text), hints, pencil marks, undo/redo, conflict highlighting, timer and stats, difficulty selection with SE grader, themes and accessibility (light/dark, font sizes, contrast), keyboard and mouse controls, keyboard-only operation.
- Out-of-scope (for now): online services, leaderboards, multiplayer, cloud saves, mobile UI, telemetry.

## Architecture
- Layered modules:
  - generator: seeded generators per variant and difficulty; ensure uniqueness and solvability; variant-constraint callbacks injected into `_fill_grid` so each variant's rules are respected during backtracking fill. The callback receives the full `VariantMetadata` as context — signature: `constraint_ok(meta: VariantMetadata, grid: Grid, row: int, col: int, val: int) -> bool`; returning `False` rejects the placement. `None` means standard (no extra constraint). The optional `meta` and `constraint_ok` parameters are added to `generate_solution` and `generate_puzzle` using an **additive, backward-compatible** approach — both parameters default to `None` so all existing positional call sites (`size, region_layout, symbols, seed`) continue to work without modification. (Q1, Option A) Variant-specific generation helpers (`JigsawRegionGenerator`, `Str8tsMaskGenerator`, `CagePartitioner`) are co-located in `solver/variant_generators.py`, imported by `generator.py` and `new_game_dialog.py` as needed. (R6 Q6, Option C) Clue counts for all variants follow `_DIFFICULTY_GIVENS = {easy: 40, medium: 32, hard: 27, expert: 23}`; for Str8ts use **density-preserving scaling** — `floor(white_cell_count × _DIFFICULTY_GIVENS[difficulty] / 81)` white cells retain given values, so clue density matches Standard proportionally regardless of black-cell mask density **(VQ-D, Option B)**; for Killer it governs the initial digit-removal phase (Hard/Expert `is_fixed` semantics subsequently reduce the effective given count toward zero); no variant-specific override table is required. (R7 Q4, Option A) The `cancel_flag: list[bool]` also propagates to `_count_solutions` and `_has_unique_solution` (both gain `cancel_flag: list[bool] | None = None`); when the flag is set mid-traversal (checked every 1 000 recursive calls), `_count_solutions` returns `0` immediately and `_has_unique_solution` returns `False` — `generate_puzzle` passes the same `cancel_flag` to both so cancellation takes effect during the uniqueness-check phase as well. (R6 Q5, Option A) To distinguish a cancelled fill from a legitimately unfillable grid, `generate_puzzle` checks `cancel_flag[0]` after `_count_solutions` returns `0` (or `_has_unique_solution` returns `False`): if `True`, the fill was cancelled and the worker propagates cancellation upward without retrying; if `False`, the grid produced no valid solution and the seed-increment retry loop continues normally. (R7 Q2, Option A) `_fill_grid` gains an optional `cell_order: list[tuple[int,int]] | None = None` parameter; when provided, backtracking iterates cells in the supplied order rather than the flat `empties` list order; `KakuroFillGenerator` passes a tightest-run-first sorted order; all other variants pass `None`. (R10 Q1, Option C) `_count_solutions` and `_has_unique_solution` gain a unified `constraint_ok: Callable | None = None` parameter (renaming the earlier `validator` parameter — **Option A chosen, R13 Q1**); when `None` the existing `validate()` is used; `KakuroFillGenerator` passes `validate_kakuro` as `constraint_ok`; `validate_kakuro` signature: `validate_kakuro(meta: VariantMetadata, grid: Grid, row: int, col: int, val: int) -> bool` (R11 Q12, Option A; R13 Q1, Option A); the `validator` name is retired everywhere — all call sites updated to use `constraint_ok`; `check_unique` delegates by passing its own `constraint_ok` arg directly to `_has_unique_solution`'s `constraint_ok` parameter with no bridging rename. (R10 Q4, Option C) A public `check_unique(meta: VariantMetadata, board_state: list[list[int]], constraint_ok: Callable | None = None, cancel_flag: list[bool] | None = None) -> bool` function is added to `solver/generator.py` as the canonical uniqueness-check entry point for complete-pipeline workers (`OneToTwentyFiveWorker`, `KenKenWorker`, `KakuroWorker`) that bypass `generate_puzzle`; internally delegates to `_has_unique_solution`; **added in Beta (GQ-2, Option B)**. (R12 Q2, Option B) `_build_peer_cache(size, region_layout, has_box_regions: bool = True)` and `_build_unit_groups(size, region_layout, has_box_regions: bool = True)` gain an explicit `has_box_regions` keyword parameter; callers pass `meta.constraints.get("has_box_regions", True)`; both `solver.py` and `difficulty_se.py` (`_WorkingGrid`) are updated at all call sites. (R10 Q2, Option A) SE score label thresholds use a single shared table for all variants in the Extended Variants phase; per-variant calibration is deferred pending a labelled test corpus (EV-T6); a `# TODO: calibrate per-variant thresholds after EV-T6 corpus` comment is left at the threshold definition in `difficulty_se.py`. (R10 Q8, Option C)
  - solver: backtracking + constraint propagation; reusable validator; deterministic.
  - model: puzzle state, candidates, undo/redo stack, timer, stats, hint limits.
  - persistence: JSON/text import/export; versioned schema; atomic save/load.
  - ui: PyQt6 widgets for grid, controls, dialogs; theme manager; accessibility.
  - services: command bus for undo/redo, hint service, conflict detection; SE difficulty rating (difficulty_se.py); variant registry at `services/variant_registry.py` — maps each `Variant` enum value to its metadata factory function and optional constraint-validator callable (Q7, Option C); each registered factory has the signature `factory(size: int) -> VariantMetadata`, returning a partial stub with the variant name, size, and an empty `constraints` dict — variant-specific fields (`region_layout`, `black_cells`, `cages`) are populated into the stub later by the background worker or dialog before the stub is passed to `GameController.new_game()`; all four in-scope variants (Standard, Jigsaw, Str8ts, Killer) register a factory, including Jigsaw — `NewGameDialog` requires a partial stub to hand to `JigsawWorker` before layout generation completes; the optional constraint-validator, if registered, retains the existing signature `constraint_ok(meta: VariantMetadata, grid: Grid, row: int, col: int, val: int) -> bool`; **Killer uses a factory pattern (GQ-C, Option A)**: the Killer registry entry provides a `"constraint_ok_factory"` key mapping to `lambda meta: _killer_constraint_ok(meta.constraints["cages"])` — a callable that takes full `VariantMetadata` and returns the live cage-aware callback after `KillerWorker` has populated `meta.constraints["cages"]`; `GameController.new_game` calls `factory = reg.get("constraint_ok_factory"); constraint_ok = factory(meta) if factory else reg.get("constraint_ok")` so all other variants (Standard, Jigsaw, Str8ts) continue using the static `reg.get("constraint_ok")` path unchanged; **this wiring is implemented in Beta (GQ-3, Option A)** — `REGISTRY[Variant.KILLER]` gains the `"constraint_ok_factory"` key and `GameController.new_game` gains the two-branch lookup now, not deferred; (R7 Q3, Option A; R7 Q5a = yes; R7 Q5b; R7 Q5c) `candidates.py` is variant-aware: in `update_all_candidates`, cells with `cell.is_black = True` are unconditionally skipped (consistent parallel treatment with `cell.is_fixed = True` cells — no candidates are assigned or updated for black cells); for Str8ts, after peer-cache elimination, each white cell's candidates are filtered to values consistent with the straight-constraint windows for that cell's row and column straights; for Killer, after peer-cache elimination, a lightweight **sum-feasibility filter** is applied (no permutation enumeration in continuous updates): candidate `v` is excluded from a cage cell when `partial_cage_sum + v > cage_sum` *or* when `remaining_empty_cells × max_remaining_unused_value < (cage_sum − partial_cage_sum)`. For KenKen, after peer-cache elimination, a **cage arithmetic feasibility filter** is applied: for `+` and `×` cages, candidate `v` is excluded when the partial sum/product including `v` already overshoots the target or the remaining cells cannot reach it; for `−` and `÷` 2-cell cages, `v` is excluded when no value in the paired cell's candidate set satisfies `|v − w| = target` or `max(v,w)/min(v,w) = target` respectively. (R11 Q2a, Option A) For Kakuro, a **run-sum/no-repeat filter** is applied: candidate `v` is excluded from a run cell when `partial_run_sum + v > run_target`, or when the remaining empty cells in that run cannot reach `(run_target − partial_run_sum − v)` using unused digits, or when `v` is already placed in another cell of the same run; each run's cell list is available from `meta.constraints["clues"]`. (R11 Q2b, Option A) All filters applied on every `update_all_candidates` call (continuous). `update_all_candidates` rebuilds the peer cache on each call via `_build_peer_cache(meta.size, meta.region_layout, meta.constraints.get("has_box_regions", True))`, ensuring variants without box regions (KenKen) always receive a correctly-shaped cache without storing it on the model. (R12 Q1, Option A) For Kakuro, `update_all_candidates` has a Kakuro-specific early branch: when `meta.name == Variant.KAKURO`, the standard `_build_peer_cache` call and peer-elimination step are skipped entirely; only the run-sum/no-repeat filter (derived from `meta.constraints["clues"]`) is applied — this avoids incorrectly removing valid candidates caused by the fact that Kakuro has no global row/column uniqueness constraint and the same digit may legally appear in multiple runs of the same row or column. (R15 Q3, Option A) `_WorkingGrid.__init__` in `difficulty_se.py` additionally zeros the candidate set for every cell with `is_black = True` before the technique loop begins, so the grader never treats black cells as candidate-bearing positions. `_WorkingGrid.__slots__` also gains a `black_cells: frozenset[tuple[int, int]]` field populated from `constraints.get("black_cells", [])` in `__init__`; `is_solved()` and `_has_empty_candidates()` both exclude positions in `black_cells`, preventing Str8ts black cells (zero candidates, `values = None`) from triggering a false `"Invalid"` verdict. (R6 Q1, Option A)
- Dependency direction: ui -> services -> model -> solver/generator; persistence depends only on model.
- `VariantMetadata.__post_init__` treats `region_layout = []` (empty list) as a valid "not yet generated" sentinel — when `region_layout` is empty the size-consistency check is skipped entirely; the background worker replaces `meta.region_layout` in-place once generation is complete; all other non-empty layouts are validated as before. (R8 Q1, Option A)
- `GameController.new_game(meta, difficulty, seed=None, hint_limit=3)` accepts a `VariantMetadata` argument so the UI new-game dialog drives which variant and difficulty to generate; the fourth keyword parameter `hint_limit: int | None = 3` carries the per-game hint cap selected in `NewGameDialog` — `None` means unlimited, any positive integer is the cap; no variant-specific `new_*_game()` overloads. (R8 Q2, Option A) The refactor of `new_game()` to accept `VariantMetadata` is performed **atomically**: the signature change, the `NewGameDialog` implementation, and all `main.py` call-site updates are done in the same implementation batch — the app will not create standard games until all three pieces land together. (Q8, Option A) `GameController._on_value_entered` adds a defensive `if cell.is_black: return` guard immediately after the existing `if cell.is_fixed: return` guard (Q6, Option A); this mirrors the `is_fixed` guard pattern for consistency even though `Board.apply_move()` and `keyPressEvent` also guard the same condition. `GameController._on_pencil_toggled` likewise gains `if cell.is_black: return` immediately after its existing `if cell.is_fixed or cell.value is not None: return` guard — black cells are never candidate-bearing and must not receive pencil marks. (R7 Q1, Option A)

## Data and Formats
- Internal board: matrix of cells with value, candidates, region id, fixed/editable flag, and `is_black` flag (Str8ts and Kakuro; `False` for all other variants). (R11 Q1, Option A) `Cell.is_black = True` marks a Str8ts or Kakuro black cell — such cells are permanently uneditable regardless of `is_fixed`; this is enforced in `Board.apply_move()` and in `SudokuGridWidget.keyPressEvent`. Blank black cells (no given digit) have `is_black = True`, `value = None`, `is_fixed = False`; given black cells have `is_black = True`, `value = N`, `is_fixed = True`.
- Variants metadata: region layouts (e.g., Jigsaw masks), constraints, symbols (1-9, 1-25).
- Save schema (JSON): version, variant, difficulty, seed, board state, timer, moves, hints used, se_score, se_label, hint_limit, undo/redo stack snapshot, theme and font settings. Schema version bumped to 2 when se_score/se_label fields are added. `hint_limit` is added with **no schema version bump** (R9 Q6, Option A): `_serialize` writes `"hint_limit": null` or `"hint_limit": N`; `_deserialize` uses `data.get("hint_limit", 3)` so existing v2 saves default to 3 on load; `SaveState.__slots__` and `__init__` gain `hint_limit: int | None = 3`; `GameController.save_game` passes `hint_limit=self._hint_limit`; schema version stays at 2. The `constraints` dict is version-neutral — variant-specific fields (black_cells, cages, etc.) live inside it and never require a schema version bump.
- Variant-specific validation failures at load time (malformed `region_layout`, `black_cells`, or `cages`) raise `ValueError` internally; `persistence.load()` catches all such `ValueError` from variant validation and re-raises as `PersistenceError(message)` — a `PersistenceError(ValueError)` subclass defined at module level in `persistence/persistence.py`; `main.py._on_open` catches `PersistenceError` and displays a `QMessageBox.critical` error dialog with the message **(VQ-C)**. Import/export: JSON primary; also support text format with rows of digits plus headers including variant, size, seed, difficulty; validation on import. Prompt user for paths on each save/load/import/export.

## UI/UX
- Grid view: selectable cells with highlight of cell/row/column/region; pencil marks visually distinct; conflict highlight without blocking input.
- Controls: new, load, save, import, export, hint, pencil toggle, undo, redo, restart; keyboard shortcuts for number entry and navigation; keyboard-only support for all actions. Arrow-key navigation skips Str8ts black cells — when movement would land on a black cell, selection continues to the next non-black cell in that direction; if all remaining cells in that direction are black, selection stays at the current cell; tab-key traversal in row-major order also skips black cells. Arrow keys **stop at the grid boundary** and do not wrap — reaching the last row/column in a direction keeps selection at the current edge cell; this matches conventional Sudoku UX; Tab/Shift-Tab continues to wrap in row-major order as before. (R7 Q7a, Option B; R7 Q7b, Option B; R8 Q7, Option A) **Navigation code structure (R9 Q8, Option B)**: arrow-key logic is extracted from the inline `nav`-dict branch in `keyPressEvent` into a new `_move_selection(dr: int, dc: int) -> None` method; `_move_selection` clamps the candidate position to `[0, size-1]` (no wrap) and scans in the `(dr, dc)` direction skipping black cells until a non-black cell is found or the boundary is hit; `_advance_selection` retains its Tab-traversal logic but gains a `skip_black: bool = True` parameter; all navigation logic is consolidated in `_move_selection` and `_advance_selection`.
- New game dialog: opening "New Game" launches a dedicated modal `NewGameDialog` (located at `src/richards_sudoku/ui/new_game_dialog.py`). The dialog has a variant selector (Standard, Jigsaw, Str8ts, Killer, 1–25, Codewords, KenKen, Kakuro), a difficulty selector (Easy, Medium, Hard, Expert), a **size selector** (an always-visible `QComboBox`; disabled and fixed at `"9×9"` for Standard, Jigsaw, Str8ts, Killer, Codewords, Kakuro; disabled and fixed at `"25×25"` for 1–25; enabled with `"4×4"`, `"6×6"`, `"9×9"` for KenKen; driven by `currentTextChanged` on the variant selector — switching variant updates and enables/disables the size control accordingly) (R10 Q5, Option B), and a **hint limit** control (a small spinner labelled "Hints: [3]▲▼ / Unlimited") for per-game hint configuration; confirming the dialog triggers generation. The selected hint limit is passed to `GameController.new_game()` and enforced during play. (R6 Q10, Option C) In Beta, the **1–25, Codewords, KenKen, and Kakuro options are all disabled (greyed out)** — each widget is present to reserve its layout position but calls `setEnabled(False)`; each option becomes active individually as its respective Extended Variant implementation batch is completed. After `dialog.exec()` returns `QDialog.DialogCode.Accepted`, `MainWindow._on_new_game` reads `.meta: VariantMetadata` and `.difficulty: str` from read-only properties on the dialog instance — the dialog does **not** emit a signal for the result; the caller pulls these properties synchronously (Q1, Option A). For Jigsaw, the dialog shows a progress spinner and an informational message ("Generating irregular regions — this may take a moment…") while region layout generation runs on a background worker (`QObject` moved onto a `QThread` — the Qt-idiomatic `moveToThread` pattern). **`NewGameDialog` owns the worker** (Q2, Option A): after the user presses Confirm on Jigsaw, the dialog transforms its own UI into the spinner state, starts the worker on the background thread, and only calls `self.accept()` after `worker.finished(region_layout)` fires — the caller therefore receives a fully-populated `meta` (including `region_layout`) when it reads `dialog.meta` after `exec()` returns. The Jigsaw progress spinner is dismissable: pressing Escape or clicking Cancel interrupts the background worker, cancels generation, and returns the user to the current board without calling `accept()`. The cancel mechanism uses a `cancel_flag: list[bool]` (a single-element mutable list, initially `[False]`) injected into `_fill_grid` as an additional keyword-argument parameter; `_fill_grid` checks `cancel_flag[0]` every 1 000 recursive calls and returns `False` immediately if the flag is set. `JigsawWorker.cancel()` sets `cancel_flag[0] = True`. (Q6, Option A) The same `moveToThread` + spinner + cancel pattern is applied to **Str8ts** (`Str8tsWorker`) and **Killer** (`KillerWorker`) generation in Beta as well — each is a `QObject` subclass moved onto a `QThread` with cancel support via the same `cancel_flag` mechanism; `NewGameDialog` displays an informational spinner for all three complex variants while generation runs. **On retry exhaustion** (all 50 retry attempts fail without cancel being set): the worker emits `error("Generation failed — please try again")`; `NewGameDialog` re-enables the Confirm button and displays the message as a status-bar toast — the same pattern used by the Extended Variant workers (`KenKenWorker`, `KakuroWorker`). (R6 Q8, Option B; GQ1) **Worker scope for Str8ts and Killer (R9 Q1, Option B)**: each background worker performs **only the slow variant-specific step** — `Str8tsWorker` calls `Str8tsMaskGenerator(seed, difficulty)` and writes `[[r,c],...]` into `meta.constraints["black_cells"]` then emits `finished(meta)`; `KillerWorker` calls `CagePartitioner(seed, difficulty, rng)` and writes the cage list into `meta.constraints["cages"]` then emits `finished(meta)`; after the dialog closes, `GameController.new_game` calls `generate_puzzle` on the **main thread** (within the ~2s performance budget). **Seed pre-generation (R9 Q2, Option A)**: `MainWindow._on_new_game` calls `random.randrange(2**31)` **before** opening `NewGameDialog`, passing this integer as `initial_seed` to the dialog constructor; the dialog and worker use this exact seed; after `exec()` returns `Accepted`, `_on_new_game` calls `new_game(meta, difficulty, seed=initial_seed, ...)` — the controller's `seed = random.randrange(2**31) if seed is None` branch is used only for Standard (no-dialog) path. For Str8ts and Killer worker retry loops, a fresh `cancel_flag = [False]` is passed to each retry attempt (so a previously-set flag cannot abort a new attempt); the worker also holds a `_stop: bool` field — `cancel()` sets both `cancel_flag[0] = True` (aborts the active retry) and `_stop = True` (prevents any further retries); before each new attempt the worker checks `self._stop` first. `CagePartitioner` accepts an optional `cancel_flag` and checks it approximately every 100 cell placements during flood-fill expansion, allowing mid-partition cancellation of `KillerWorker` generation. (R7 Q8a, Option C; R7 Q8b, Option C)
- Themes/accessibility: light/dark presets; adjustable font size (min 6pt); avoid color-only cues; default Arial font; palette and additional fonts to be supplied later. The `Palette` dataclass in `theme.py` gains four new fields for variant-specific colours: `black_cell_bg: str` (dark background for Str8ts black cells), `cage_member_bg: str` (subtle cage-peer highlight tint for Killer), `cage_label_color: str` (Killer cage sum label text colour), and `cage_dash_pattern: tuple[float, ...]` (QPen dash pattern for thin intra-cage edges in Killer and KenKen; e.g. `(4.0, 2.0)` for a short dash); both `LIGHT` and `DARK` `Palette` instances must supply values for all four new fields. (Q3, Option A; VQ5)
- Feedback: toast/dialog for save/load/import/export success/failure; hint count visible; timer visible and pauses on save; SE difficulty rating (score + category) displayed in status bar on new game and load; SE score/label also persisted in save file and restored without recomputing. The end-of-game stats summary is a **custom `GameCompleteDialog(QDialog)` subclass** (R9 Q4, Option A) using `QVBoxLayout` — labels display SE score/label, elapsed time, move count, and hint count; three `QPushButton` objects are wired with direct signal connections: **OK** (`reject()` — dismiss), **New Game** (`done(GameCompleteDialog.Result.NEW_GAME)` — open `NewGameDialog`), **Restart** (`done(GameCompleteDialog.Result.RESTART)` — keep-timer restart); `MainWindow._on_game_complete` inspects the integer result code after `exec()` and dispatches the corresponding action; the existing `QMessageBox.information` call is replaced entirely. (R7 Q9, Option C; R9 Q4, Option A)

## Behavior
- New game: select variant and difficulty; generate with seed; validate solvable and unique; start timer.
- Hint: `GameController.hint(mode: str)` receives the hint mode explicitly on each call — `mode` is one of `"show_candidate"`, `"auto_fill"`, `"multi_reveal"`, `"walkthrough"`; `MainWindow` passes the currently-selected mode from a **`QButtonGroup` of four radio buttons added as a widget in the status bar** (R9 Q5, Option C); the selected mode persists between invocations until changed; `hint_limit: int | None` is stored on the controller; `None` = unlimited; only `auto_fill` and `multi_reveal` decrement the hint counter; `show_candidate` and `walkthrough` are advisory and never consume a hint; track count; filling hints lock cells immediately (`is_fixed = True`). (R8 Q5, Option A) **All four hint modes fully implemented in Beta (R9 Q3, Option A)**: `auto_fill` — fills one randomly-chosen empty cell from the solution and locks it; `show_candidate` — does **not** fill; highlights valid candidates for the currently-selected empty cell (no limit decrement); `multi_reveal` — fills three randomly-chosen empty cells at once, all locked; `walkthrough` — uses the SE grader to identify the lowest-weight firing technique, highlights the affected cells' eliminations without auto-filling (no limit decrement).
- Undo/redo: unbounded stack (practically capped by memory guard); operates on board edits and pencil marks only; timer and hint counters unaffected.
- Conflict detection: **continuous** checks on every board refresh (each value entered or deleted). Flags **all** conflicting cell pairs on the board regardless of which cell is selected — if two cells in the same row/column/region share the same value, both are highlighted with `conflict_bg` even when neither is the selected cell; `_conflict_cells` is replaced by a board-wide `_all_conflict_cells(board, size, region_layout)` helper that returns the complete set of cells involved in any duplication conflict. (R8 Q6, Option A) `_all_conflict_cells` is computed **unconditionally whenever `meta is not None`** — conflicting cells are always visible regardless of whether any cell is currently selected; the conflicts computation in `_draw_board` must be moved **outside** the `if sel and meta:` guard into a separate `if meta:` guard, with only `peers` computation remaining inside the selection guard; a player loading a puzzle with pre-existing conflicts sees them highlighted immediately on first render. **(GQ-D: confirmed unconditional)** (R9 Q9, Option A) For Str8ts, also continuously checks that each white straight can still be completed to a consecutive run. For Killer, also continuously flags cells in any cage whose partial state is provably wrong: partial sum already exceeds the cage target, or the remaining empty cells cannot reach the target given available distinct candidates. For KenKen, also flags row and column duplicates (no box-region conflicts apply since `has_box_regions=False`); also flags cage cells whose partial arithmetic is provably violated (same criteria as Killer). For Kakuro, flags only intra-run conflicts: duplicate digits within a run, and cells whose run partial-sum exceeds or cannot reach the clue target — global row/column conflict highlighting does not apply to Kakuro. `_all_conflict_cells(board, size, region_layout, meta=None)` gains a `meta` keyword parameter to dispatch variant-specific conflict detection: for KenKen it skips box-unit scanning; for Kakuro it replaces row/col/region scanning with run-based scanning entirely. (R11 Q3, Option A) All highlighting is updated on every `value_entered` signal without a separate "Check" action.
- Persistence: save/load is atomic; load restores timer, stats, candidates, pencil marks, undo/redo.
- Restart: a **Restart** menu item in the Game menu offers two paths — (a) **Restart** (keep timer): resets all player-entered values to the initial clue state while the elapsed timer continues running; (b) **Restart and Reset Timer**: same board reset plus timer reset to zero. Implemented as two `QAction` entries (`_act_restart` F9, `_act_restart_timer` Shift+F9) inside a `"&Restart"` `QMenu` submenu added to the Game menu **(GQ-B: submenu nesting is acceptable; "two separate QAction entries in the Game menu" is satisfied by two distinct actions at any nesting depth)**; move and hint counters are **not** reset in Beta; the undo/redo stack **is** cleared on both sub-actions — there is no meaningful editing history to preserve after a board reset. (R6 Q9, Option A; R7 Q6, Option B)

## Performance Targets
- Validation: <200ms typical 9x9; solving: <2s typical 9x9 on baseline hardware; scales reasonably for larger grids.
- UI responsiveness: no blocked input during generation/solve; use background workers with progress cues.
- Save/load/import/export: <300ms typical; guard against data loss with temp file then move.
- Memory: bounded candidate tracking and undo/redo; avoid quadratic growth on 1–25 grids.

## Testing
- Unit: solver correctness, generator uniqueness/solvability per difficulty, conflict detection, hint correctness (per hint mode), undo/redo integrity (board edits/pencil marks), stats tracking, persistence round-trip.
- Property/scenario: randomized seeds across variants and sizes; invariants on constraints; import/export fixtures.
- UI smoke: grid render, selection/highlight, pencil marks visibility, hint button availability/modes, undo/redo, theme toggle, keyboard-only flows.
- Performance: benchmarks for solver/generator and persistence budgets; deterministic seeds in tests.
- Tooling: pytest, pytest-qt (qtbot), hypothesis optional.

- Hint limit sentinel: `hint_limit = None` means unlimited; any positive `int` is the cap. Persisted in save JSON as `"hint_limit": null` (unlimited) or `"hint_limit": N`; restored on load. (R8 Q4, Option A)
- Text import/export (Standard and all variants): the text format uses a **header block** followed by digit rows. Header fields: `variant: <name>`, `size: <N>`, `seed: <N>`, `difficulty: <label>`; body is one row per board row with digits and `0` for empty (e.g. `530070000`). Variant-specific fields (Jigsaw `region_layout`, Str8ts `mask`, Killer `cages`) are extra header lines appended after the core four. Validation on import checks header completeness and digit count; missing seed defaults to `0`. (R8 Q10, Option A)

## Variant Specifications

### `Variant` Enum
- `STANDARD = "standard"` — classic 9×9
- `JIGSAW = "jigsaw"` — irregular regions
- `STR8TS = "str8ts"` — straights with black cells
- `KILLER = "killer"` — cage sums (add this; was an oversight)
- `ONE_TO_25 = "1to25"` — 1–25 symbol variant (rename from previous `EXTENDED`; `EXTENDED` is retired); the identifier `1TO25` starts with a digit and is not valid Python — the correct enum name is `ONE_TO_25`. **Silent backward-compat migration (R9 Q7, Option A)**: both `VariantMetadata.from_dict` and `Board.from_dict` check the raw variant string; if it equals `"extended"` it is silently substituted with `"1to25"` before calling `Variant(...)`; existing save files carrying `"variant": "extended"` load without error; no `DeprecationWarning` is emitted; no schema version bump needed.
- `CODEWORDS = "codewords"` — letter-substitution variant; letters A–I substitute for digits 1–9; a bijective codebook maps each letter to a unique digit; planned for Extended Variants phase.
- `KENKEN = "kenken"` — arithmetic cage variant; row and column uniqueness only (Latin-square rules, no box regions); cages carry one of +, −, ×, ÷ with a target value; planned for Extended Variants phase.
- `KAKURO = "kakuro"` — crossword-sum variant; run-sum and no-repeat-per-run constraints (no global row/column or box uniqueness); black header cells carry across/down clue numbers; planned for Extended Variants phase.

### Jigsaw Sudoku
- **Grid**: 9×9 with irregular (jigsaw-shaped) regions replacing the standard 3×3 boxes. Each region contains exactly 9 cells in a connected, non-rectangular layout.
- **`Variant` enum value**: `Variant.JIGSAW = "jigsaw"` (already present in the enum).
- **Constraints**: standard row and column uniqueness apply unchanged; region uniqueness uses the irregular layout instead of fixed boxes.
- **Region layout**: stored in `VariantMetadata.region_layout` as a 9×9 matrix of integer region IDs (0–8). Each cell belongs to exactly one region; all regions have exactly 9 cells.
- **Region generation algorithm**: generate at runtime, seeded by puzzle seed. Start from the standard 3×3-box layout; perform iterative cell-swap between adjacent regions — a swap is valid only if both regions remain connected (no isolated cell) after the swap. Irregularity is difficulty-scaled: Easy applies 1–2 swaps (shapes barely deviate from standard boxes); Medium applies moderate swaps; Hard and Expert apply many swaps producing fully irregular shapes. Generation runs on a background worker; the UI shows a modal progress dialog with a spinner and the message "Generating irregular regions — this may take a moment…" while work is in progress.
- **Generator**: backtracking fill using the irregular `region_layout` passed into `_fill_grid` — **no variant-constraint callback is required for Jigsaw**. `_build_peer_cache` derives peer sets directly from `region_layout`, so standard peer-uniqueness enforcement during backtracking is sufficient to ensure region uniqueness. (`_fill_grid` does accept an optional `constraint_ok` parameter added for Str8ts/Killer; Jigsaw passes `None`.) Follow with clue removal using uniqueness check (`_count_solutions` / `_has_unique_solution`; revert if not unique); difficulty controls both region irregularity and clue count.
- **Solver/validator**: identical to standard except unit groups are derived dynamically from `region_layout` rather than fixed 3×3 boxes.
- **SE grader**: region-agnostic; all standard techniques apply using the variant-derived unit groups.
- **Persistence**: `region_layout` is stored at its existing top-level position in `variant_meta` JSON — **not** inside `constraints`; no serialization format change is needed **(VQ-3, Option A)**. `persistence.load()` validates 9×9 shape and exactly 9 cells per region for Jigsaw (in `VariantMetadata.__post_init__` or `_deserialize`), raising `ValueError` wrapped in `PersistenceError` on failure. No schema version bump required.
- **UI — borders**: `_draw_lines` is replaced by a unified `_draw_edges` method handling all variants via `region_layout` comparison; the arithmetic `i % box_rows` thick-line logic becomes a special case for Standard/Str8ts where adjacent cells in the same region always have matching arithmetic IDs. All variants use the same code path. The method signature is `_draw_edges(painter, size, cell_size, edge_thickness, pal, dash_thin: bool = False)` where `edge_thickness: dict[tuple[int, int, str], bool]` maps `(row, col, "H"|"V")` edge keys to `True` (thick) or `False` (thin); `dash_thin=True` causes thin edges to be drawn with `pal.cage_dash_pattern` — `_draw_board` passes `dash_thin=(meta.name == Variant.KILLER)`; no variant logic lives inside `_draw_edges` **(GQ-1, Option A)**; `_draw_board` pre-builds the edge dict (performing all variant-specific edge logic there) before passing it to `_draw_edges`, which is a pure rendering function. The edge dict is pre-computed by private helper `_build_edge_dict(meta, size, box_rows, box_cols) -> dict[tuple[int,int,str], bool]` that `_draw_board` delegates to, keeping `_draw_board` readable **(VQ-A)**. (Q5, Option B) **Edge key convention (Q4, Option B)**: `(r, c, "H")` identifies the horizontal edge **above** row `r` (between row `r−1` and row `r`); `(r, c, "V")` identifies the vertical edge **to the left** of column `c` (between col `c−1` and col `c`). Outer border keys where `r == 0` or `c == 0` are always thick (grid boundary).
- **UI — selection highlight**: cell selection highlights peers in the same row, column, and region. Pencil mark behaviour unchanged from standard.
- **Import/export**: text format header includes `"variant: jigsaw"` and a `"region_layout"` field serialised as 9 successive `region_layout:` header lines using the repeating-field convention, each with 9 space-separated integer region IDs (e.g. `region_layout: 0 0 0 1 1 1 2 2 2`); one `region_layout:` line per board row written after the core header block **(VQ-B)**.

### Str8ts
- **Grid**: 9×9 with black and white cells. Black cells divide each row and column into contiguous "straights" (runs of white cells).
- **Constraints**:
  - Each straight (run of white cells between two black cells or a black cell and the grid edge) must contain a set of consecutive integers in any order (e.g., 3-4-5 or 7-8-9). No duplicates within a straight. The straight constraint is enforced independently on **both rows and columns**.
  - Rows and columns must contain no duplicate digits across all white cells in that line.
  - Black cells may hold a pre-given digit (shown shaded); given black digits obey row/column uniqueness but do not contribute to straight sequences. Whether black cells carry given digits is **difficulty-dependent**: Easy puzzles show pre-given digits in all black cells (100 % exposure); Medium exposes `floor(total_black_cells × DIFFICULTY_GIVENS["medium"] / DIFFICULTY_GIVENS["easy"])` = `floor(total_black_cells × 0.8)` black cells (80 % — same fraction as the density-preserving clue-count formula; GQ8); Hard and Expert black cells carry no given digits.
- **`Cell.is_black`**: Str8ts black cells carry `is_black = True`. Blank black cells (no given digit): `is_black = True`, `value = None`, `is_fixed = False`. Given black cells: `is_black = True`, `value = N`, `is_fixed = True`. `Board.apply_move()` raises `ValueError` for any cell where `is_black = True`, preventing player edits. `SudokuGridWidget.keyPressEvent` additionally suppresses digit input when `cell.is_black` is `True`.
- **Metadata**: `meta.constraints["black_cells"]` = list of `[row, col]` pairs identifying black cell positions. All other cells are white.
- **Generation strategy**: `Str8tsWorker` generates the black-cell mask by calling `Str8tsMaskGenerator(seed, difficulty)` and writes the resulting `[[r,c],...]` list into `meta.constraints["black_cells"]` **before** passing `meta` to `generate_puzzle`; `generate_puzzle` only reads `meta.constraints["black_cells"]` and never instantiates `Str8tsMaskGenerator` itself. (R8 Q3, Option A) `generate_puzzle` then contains a Str8ts-specific **pre-processing step** triggered when `meta.name == Variant.STR8TS`: (1) pre-populates black cells that carry a given digit (marking them `is_fixed = True`), and (2) removes all black-cell positions from the `empties` list before `_fill_grid` is called, so backtracking never attempts to fill a black cell. The mask is therefore always present in `meta` when `generate_puzzle` is called; **non-trivial straight** is defined as a run of white cells of length ≥ 2 — the mask guarantees at least one such run per row and column in both axes (R6 Q3a, Option A). **Mask density is difficulty-dependent** (R6 Q3b, Option B): Easy 10 %; Medium 15 %; Hard 20 %; Expert 25 % — a linear progression confirmed as the canonical values (VQ1; spec authoritative over code). Easy generates fewer black cells (longer, simpler straights); Expert generates the most (more partitions, shorter straights). The difficulty-dependent given-digit exposure rate is applied on top of the density-varied mask. After `_fill_grid` returns, a **post-validate consecutiveness check** is performed: every straight segment (in every row and column) is verified to contain a consecutive set of digits (e.g. {3,4,5} is valid; {1,3,5} is not); if any straight fails, the entire fill is discarded and retried with the next seed value (seed + 1 per retry); the retry loop runs until a fully consecutive layout is produced, bounded by a configurable maximum retry count. After a valid fill is confirmed, final clue removal uses a uniqueness check. Given black-cell digits are exposed according to difficulty tier. (Q2, Option A)
- **Solver/validator**: apply standard row/column uniqueness plus run-sequence validity check for each white straight segment in every row **and** column; invalid if any straight cannot form a consecutive run with remaining candidates.
- **Continuous candidate filter algorithm**: for `update_all_candidates` in Str8ts, each white cell uses an **exact test per candidate**: for each candidate `v`, verify that substituting `v` into the straight's already-placed values still allows the remaining empty cells in that straight to form a valid consecutive run (i.e. check that a set of distinct integers exists that extends `placed ∪ {v}` to a consecutive run of `straight_length` integers within 1–9); exclude `v` if no such completion exists. This exact algorithm is implemented once in a shared helper (e.g. `_can_extend_straight(placed: set[int], length: int, v: int) -> bool`) called by both `update_all_candidates` and `_Str8tsRun` in the SE grader — one implementation, two callers. (R8 Q8, Option A)
- **Difficulty SE**: `_Str8tsRun` technique (weight 1.7) eliminates candidate values outside valid consecutive-run windows for each white straight segment in both row and column directions.
- **Persistence**: JSON save includes `"variant": "str8ts"` and `meta.constraints["black_cells"]` as `"black_cells"` array; given black cell digits serialised in the board state with `is_fixed: true`. Stored inside `constraints` dict — no schema version bump required.
- **UI**: black cells rendered with a filled dark background (`is_black = True` drives rendering regardless of `is_fixed`); pencil marks shown in white cells only; no cage-sum labels. The background colour rendering priority chain in `_draw_board` for all cells is: `selected > conflict > peer > fixed > is_black (dark bg) > base`. This means: blank black cells (`is_black=True, is_fixed=False`) are rendered with the `black_cell_bg` palette colour; given black cells (`is_black=True, is_fixed=True`) are rendered with `fixed_bg` (which takes precedence) — this is intentional, distinguishing unclued black squares from clued ones by their background. (Q4, Option B)
- **UI — peer highlight**: when a white cell is selected, black cells in the same row and column are also highlighted as peers (same peer-background tint), consistent with all other peer cells. Black cells always retain their dark base background when not highlighted.
- **Import/export**: text format header includes `"variant: str8ts"`; black cell mask encoded as a compact mask row string where each row is a string of `.` (white) and `B` (black) characters, joined by `/` (e.g. `mask: .B..B...B/.B....B../...`). Coordinates of given black digits expressed as separate `black_givens: [[r,c,v],...]` entry.

### Killer Sudoku
- **`Variant` enum value**: `Variant.KILLER = "killer"` — add to the enum.
- **Grid**: standard 9×9 with standard 3×3 box regions (identical layout to classic Sudoku).
- **Constraints**:
  - All standard Sudoku row, column, and 3×3 box uniqueness constraints apply.
  - Grid is partitioned into non-overlapping "cages" covering all 81 cells. Each cage has an associated sum target; the digits within a cage must sum exactly to that target. No digit may repeat within a cage.
- **Cage rules**: cage sizes typically 1–5 cells; single-cell cages are functionally givens. No cage may span more cells than the maximum without repeating a digit (e.g., max sum for 2-cell cage is 17 = 9+8).
- **Metadata**: `meta.constraints["cages"]` = list of `{"cells": [[r,c], ...], "sum": N}` dicts; cages are non-overlapping and cover all 81 cells exactly.
- **Generator**: start from a valid sudoku solution using a single `random.Random(puzzle_seed)` instance; the **same RNG instance** is passed through and used in sequence for all three phases — solution fill via `_fill_grid`, cage partitioning via `CagePartitioner`, and clue removal via the uniqueness-check loop — so replaying the same `puzzle_seed` yields identical solution, cage layout, and clue pattern end-to-end. (R8 Q9, Option A) Partition cells into cages via random flood-fill expansion from seed cells — difficulty controls cage size distribution (Easy avg 2–3 cells, Medium avg 3–4, Hard/Expert avg 4–5); compute cage sums from solution; remove all digits leaving only cage boundaries and sums. Uniqueness is verified by extending `_count_solutions` / `_has_unique_solution` with the same optional `constraint_ok` callback as `_fill_grid` (Q4, Option A); the Killer cage-constraint callable is passed so the uniqueness check is cage-aware; generation retries with a different partition seed if not unique.
- **`is_fixed` semantics**: difficulty-dependent. For Easy, single-cell cages are stored with `is_fixed = True` (rendered bold and protected from player editing, acting as given clues). For Medium, the exact algorithm is: sort all cages by size ascending; take the first `floor(len(cages) * 0.3)` cages from that sorted list; mark every cell in those cages `is_fixed = True`; remaining cages are player-editable. For Hard and Expert, all cells start `is_fixed = False` and the player fills everything in.
- **SE grader seeding for Killer**: `_WorkingGrid` seeds its working copy using cage-constraint analysis rather than `is_fixed` clues alone (since Hard/Expert Killer boards have zero `is_fixed = True` cells). A Killer-specific seeding path in `_WorkingGrid.__init__` runs in two steps (R6 Q2, Option C): (1) call `set_value()` for every single-cell cage (the cage sum is the cell's only possible value); (2) run `_killer_cage_step()` once and then apply naked-singles propagation, calling `set_value()` for any cell that becomes a naked single purely from cage-constraint narrowing; this maximises pre-seeded information before the main technique loop begins.
- **`is_complete` check**: for Killer, `GameController.is_complete` must additionally verify that all cage sums are satisfied (sum of filled cell values in each cage equals the cage target) — row/column/region uniqueness alone is insufficient. This check is **inline in `GameController.is_complete`** (Q5, Option A): after the standard `validate()` call passes, if `self._meta.name == Variant.KILLER`, iterate `self._meta.constraints["cages"]` and confirm each cage's sum; `solver.validate()` is not extended. The controller accesses the constraint dict directly.
- **Solver/validator**: standard constraints plus cage sum validation at each placement step; prune when partial cage sum exceeds target or remaining cells cannot reach it; uniqueness count uses this cage-aware solver.
- **Difficulty SE**: `_KillerCage` technique (weight 1.9) uses permutation enumeration to restrict per-cell candidates to values appearing in any valid cage assignment that satisfies the sum and no-repeat rule.
- **Cage permutation safety**: for cages of 5+ cells enumerate with early pruning (prune when partial sum exceeds target or value already used); cap enumeration at a configurable bound (default 10 000 permutations); when the cap is reached, return `[grid.candidates[r][c].copy() for (r, c) in cells]` — preserve the current (already-narrowed) per-cell candidate sets and suppress further enumeration for that cage call; this is always safe (never eliminates a legitimate candidate, but may leave some eliminations for a subsequent invocation). (R6 Q4, Option C)
- **Persistence**: JSON save includes `"variant": "killer"` and `"cages"` array in metadata. Stored inside `constraints` dict — no schema version bump required.
- **UI — cage sum label**: the cage sum floats as a small overlay in the top-left corner of each cage's topmost-leftmost cell (proportionally ~20–25% of cell height); the player's digit remains full-size and centred in the cell; the label and digit do not overlap. "Topmost-leftmost" is defined as row-major minimum: minimum row first, then minimum column within that row (i.e. `min(cells, key=lambda rc: (rc[0], rc[1]))`). In Killer cells that have a cage-sum label and **no entered player digit**, the 3×3 pencil mark grid is shifted downward (and/or rightward) by the height of the cage-sum label area, ensuring no pencil mark position overlaps the cage-sum overlay. (R6 Q7, Option B).
- **UI — cage boundaries**: rendered by the unified `_draw_edges` method using a per-edge approach. For each internal cell edge, compare cage membership of the two adjacent cells (looked up from `constraints["cages"]`); edges shared by cells of the *same* cage are drawn thin/absent; edges between cells of *different* cages use the **same thick pen as standard box borders** — no additional visual distinction is needed because Killer uses standard 3×3 regions, so every box-border edge already separates cells from different cages anyway. All outer grid borders remain standard.
- **UI — conflict highlighting**: flags cells with standard row/column/region duplicates **and** cells belonging to a cage whose partially-filled values are provably wrong: partial sum already exceeds the cage target, or remaining empty cells cannot reach the target given remaining distinct candidates.
- **UI — cage member highlight**: selecting any Killer cell also subtly shades all other cells in the same cage. The cage-member tint (`Palette.cage_member_bg`) is placed between peer highlight and fixed background in the `_draw_board` priority chain: `selected > conflict > peer > cage_member > fixed > is_black > base`. A cage-member cell already in the peer set will render as peer (stronger tint wins). (Q3, Option A)
- **Hint behaviour for Killer**: after a hint fills a cell (regardless of `is_fixed` state), that cell is immediately locked (`is_fixed = True`) so the player cannot overwrite or erase the hint value. This applies to all variants uniformly.
- **Import/export**: text format header includes `"variant: killer"` and Killer cages use the repeating-field format — one `cage:` header line per cage: `cage: r,c r,c r,c:N` (cell coordinates space-separated as `row,col` pairs, colon before the sum `N`; e.g. `cage: 0,0 0,1 1,0:15`) (VQ4).

### 1–25 Sudoku
- **Grid**: 25×25 with 25 non-overlapping 5×5 box regions. Each region contains exactly 25 cells in a 5-row × 5-column layout, mirroring the Standard 9×9 structure scaled to 5×5 sub-grids.
- **Constraints**: standard row, column, and 5×5 box uniqueness using symbols 1–25; structurally identical to Standard 9×9, scaled to 25 symbols and a 25×25 grid.
- **`Variant` enum value**: `Variant.ONE_TO_25 = "1to25"` (already present; `NewGameDialog` option is **greyed out in Beta**; enabled in Extended Variants phase).
- **Metadata**: `meta.size = 25`; `meta.symbols = list(range(1, 26))`; `meta.region_layout` = standard 5×5 box layout (25×25 matrix; region IDs 0–24, each covering one 5×5 block).
- **Generator**: backtracking fill identical in structure to Standard, scaled to 25 symbols and a 25×25 grid; `_DIFFICULTY_GIVENS` clue counts scaled proportionally as `floor(givens_9x9 × 625 / 81)` (where 625 = 25² and 81 = 9²); `_fill_grid` receives no variant-constraint callback; uniqueness check via `_count_solutions` / `_has_unique_solution`; **background worker mandatory** — `OneToTwentyFiveWorker(QObject)` moved onto `QThread` using same `moveToThread` + `cancel_flag` + `_stop` pattern as Str8ts/Killer workers. Unlike Str8ts/Killer workers (which perform only the variant-specific step and defer final `generate_puzzle` to the main thread), `OneToTwentyFiveWorker` performs the **complete generation pipeline** on the background thread — 25×25 solution fill, clue removal, and uniqueness check — and emits `finished(meta)` with a fully-generated puzzle; `GameController.new_game` receives the complete meta and does not call `generate_puzzle`. (R11 Q5, Option C) Uniqueness is verified via `check_unique(meta, board_state, cancel_flag=cancel_flag)` (R12 Q2, Option B). `OneToTwentyFiveWorker` creates `rng = random.Random(seed)` once and threads this single instance through both phases (solution fill and clue-removal uniqueness loop); no per-phase re-seeding — per-phase fresh `random.Random(seed)` applies only to workers with a separate cage-partitioner or template-generator phase (KenKen, Kakuro). `CodewordsWorker` also uses a single threaded `rng = random.Random(seed)` instance for all pipeline steps — bijection shuffle is a trivial operation, not a structurally separate phase in the cage-partitioner/template-generator sense; no per-phase re-seeding. (R13 Q2, Option B; R14 Q2, Option A; R15 Q4, Option C)
- **Performance budget**: generation < 30 s on baseline hardware; solving < 10 s; SE grading < 1 s; all operations run on background workers; cancel is always available.
- **Solver/validator**: identical to Standard; `_build_unit_groups` and `_build_peer_cache` scale naturally to any size via the `size` parameter.
- **SE grader**: all standard techniques apply with 25-symbol candidate sets; `_build_unit_groups(25, region_layout)` produces 75 units (25 rows + 25 cols + 25 regions); no new techniques required; performance budget for `grade()` extends proportionally.
- **Persistence**: JSON with `"variant": "1to25"`, `"size": 25`, and the standard 25×25 board state matrix; no extra `constraints` fields (standard 5×5 layout is implicit in `meta.size`).
- **UI**: `SudokuGridWidget` auto-scales `cell_size` from viewport for 25×25 (minimum 14 px per cell); 2-digit symbol display; font size auto-adjusts within the min-6pt guarantee; scrollable grid area when viewport is too small — `SudokuGridWidget` is wrapped in a `QScrollArea` in `MainWindow`'s central layout; `SudokuGridWidget.sizeHint()` returns `size × cell_size + border margins`; `QScrollArea` provides scroll bars when the grid exceeds the viewport with no changes to `_draw_board` painting internals beyond `sizeHint()` (R12 Q6, Option A); same selection and highlight patterns as all variants; `_draw_board` uses `box_rows = box_cols = 5` for the thick-border arithmetic.
- **Import/export**: text format header `"variant: 1to25"`, `"size: 25"`; digit rows use space-separated values (e.g. `5 14 0 22 ...`); empty = `0`.

### Codewords Sudoku
- **Grid**: 9×9 with standard 3×3 box regions.
- **Constraints**: standard row, column, and 3×3 box uniqueness (same as Standard at the digit layer); cells display **letters A–I** instead of digits 1–9; a hidden bijective **codebook** assigns each letter to a unique digit 1–9; the puzzle reveals a difficulty-dependent subset of the codebook as given clues, and the player deduces the remainder.
- **`Variant` enum value**: `Variant.CODEWORDS = "codewords"`.
- **Metadata**: `meta.constraints["codebook"]` = `{letter: digit}` dict (9 entries, full bijection — persisted but hidden from the player at runtime); `meta.constraints["given_mappings"]` = `{letter: digit}` dict containing only the entries revealed as clues; `meta.size = 9`.
- **Letter layer**: cell values are stored and solved at the digit layer (1–9); the letter-display layer is a pure view mapping: `display(v) = inverse_codebook[v]`. Candidates are maintained as digit sets in `candidates.py`; `SudokuGridWidget` converts to letter display for rendering. No changes to model logic — only the rendering and persistence layers see letters.
- **Generator** (runs on `CodewordsWorker`, same `moveToThread` + cancel pattern): `CodewordsWorker.run()` calls `CodewordsGenerator.generate()` as its main action — `CodewordsGenerator` encapsulates all five steps and `CodewordsWorker` wraps it for thread/cancel management; L1 (`CodewordsGenerator`) is the real implementation and L2 (`CodewordsWorker`) is the shell. (R13 Q6, Option A) `CodewordsGenerator.generate()`: (1) generate a valid standard 9×9 solution via backtracking; (2) construct a random bijective `letter → digit` mapping (uniform shuffle of A–I → 1–9); (3) remove digits to a difficulty-appropriate clue count (same `_DIFFICULTY_GIVENS` table as Standard); (4) select `given_mappings` entries to reveal — difficulty-scaled count: Easy ≥ 5 revealed pairs; Medium 3–4; Hard 2; Expert ≤ 1 (Expert may reveal 0 when the mapping is uniquely inferrable from the grid alone); (5) verify unique solution using `check_unique(meta, board_state, cancel_flag=cancel_flag)` at the digit layer — the codebook mapping is fixed during generation, so digit-layer uniqueness fully determines puzzle uniqueness (no codebook permutation enumeration required); (R11 Q6, Option A) `CodewordsGenerator` uses a **single** `rng = random.Random(seed)` instance threaded through all five steps — bijection shuffle is a trivial operation, not a structurally separate phase; no per-phase re-seeding (R15 Q4, Option C). `CodewordsWorker` performs **all five pipeline steps** on the background thread (same pattern as `KenKenWorker` and `OneToTwentyFiveWorker`) and emits `finished(meta)` with a fully-generated puzzle; `GameController.new_game` receives complete meta and does not call `generate_puzzle`. (R12 Q4, Option B)
- **Solver/validator**: identical to Standard at the digit layer; additionally validates bijection consistency on each placement: if two cells bearing the same letter have conflicting forced digit values, the board is invalid; enforced via `_CODEWORDS_BIJECTION_CACHE` built at the start of each solve call in `solver/solver.py` from `meta.constraints["codebook"]`; the cache is local to the solve invocation, not persistent module state. (R11 Q7, Option A)
- **`is_complete` check**: `GameController.is_complete` uses the standard grid completion check for Codewords (all cells filled and valid at the digit layer); no additional codebook consistency check is applied because standard Sudoku validity at the digit layer implies a consistent bijection given the fixed codebook. (R11 Q4, Option B)
- **SE grader**: `_CodewordsMapping` technique (weight 1.3) fires before standard techniques when **every** cell bearing an unassigned letter `L` is already a digit-singleton **and** all of those singletons agree on the same digit `d`; any cell still carrying multiple candidates for letter `L` blocks the technique from firing for that letter entirely — the technique relies on all cells having converged to the same singleton, not on computing intersection narrowing (R14 Q7, Option B); propagates the letter-to-digit assignment and eliminates `d` from the candidate sets of all cells bearing other unassigned letters. All remaining standard techniques apply at the digit layer. `_WorkingGrid` is pre-seeded from `is_fixed` cells plus `given_mappings` entries: for each `(letter, digit)` pair in `given_mappings`, `_WorkingGrid.__init__` iterates all board cells and calls `set_value(r, c, digit)` for every cell whose corresponding letter matches the mapping key — all instances of that letter are locked to their digit in the working copy before the technique loop begins, mirroring `is_fixed` pre-seeding but driven by the letter mapping. (R13 Q7, Option A)
- **Persistence**: JSON includes `"variant": "codewords"`, `meta.constraints["codebook"]` (full bijection), and `meta.constraints["given_mappings"]` (revealed subset); stored in `constraints` dict; no schema version bump.
- **UI — display layer**: `SudokuGridWidget` renders cell values as letters (A–I) when `meta.name == Variant.CODEWORDS`; confirmed entries use the standard confirmed colour; pencil marks display as letter candidates. A **Codebook Panel** implemented as a `QDockWidget` (default dock position: bottom of the main window; player can undock and reposition) (R12 Q5, Option C) wraps a compact horizontal 9-slot strip (A–I, each with a digit field); given-mapping slots are bold/locked; player-hypothesis slots are editable; hidden (`setVisible(False)`) for non-Codewords variants, shown on `new_game` and `load` when `meta.name == Variant.CODEWORDS`; keyboard-navigable for accessibility.
- **UI — codebook interaction**: the panel is an optional aid — the puzzle is completable by operating purely on the letter grid without explicit panel entries.
- **Hint behaviour for Codewords**: `show_candidate` maps digit candidates through the inverse codebook before display so the player sees letter candidates (A–I) consistent with the letter-display mode rather than raw digit candidates. (R10 Q9a, Option B) `walkthrough` may highlight a codebook panel entry as the deducible next step when `_CodewordsMapping` is the lowest-weight firing technique — the walkthrough message points to the panel slot and explains the forced letter-to-digit assignment without consuming a hint counter. `auto_fill` targets grid cells only and never fills a codebook panel entry. (R10 Q9b, Option C)
- **Import/export**: text header `"variant: codewords"`, `"codebook: A=1,B=2,..."` (full 9-pair bijection) (R12 Q7, Option A), `"given_mappings: A=3,C=7,..."` (revealed subset only); on import both fields are required — `codebook` enables full reconstruction and validation; `given_mappings` designates which entries are locked as given clues; digit rows use letter characters (A–I; `_` for empty cell).

### KenKen
- **Grid**: N×N for N ∈ {4, 6, 9}; default size for new games is 9; digits 1–N fill each row and column exactly once; **no 3×3 box uniqueness** — KenKen is a Latin-square variant.
- **Constraints**: row uniqueness (digits 1–N, no repeat); column uniqueness (digits 1–N, no repeat); **cage arithmetic**: grid partitioned into non-overlapping cages covering all N×N cells; each cage has a target value and one operation — `+` (sum: any size ≥ 1); `×` (product: any size ≥ 1); `−` (difference: exactly 2 cells, `|v₁ − v₂| = target`); `÷` (quotient: exactly 2 cells, `max(v₁,v₂) / min(v₁,v₂) = target`, must be exact integer); single-cell cages have no operation and their target equals the cell value (acts as a given clue).
- **`Variant` enum value**: `Variant.KENKEN = "kenken"`.
- **Metadata**: `meta.size` ∈ {4, 6, 9}; `meta.constraints["cages"]` = list of `{"cells": [[r,c],...], "op": "+"|"-"|"*"|"/"|"", "target": N}` dicts (empty string `op` for single-cell givens); `meta.constraints["has_box_regions"]` = `False`; no `region_layout` used — `_build_peer_cache` and `_build_unit_groups` receive `has_box_regions=False` and omit box units from the peer cache and unit groups. (R10 Q2, Option A)
- **Generator** (runs on `KenKenWorker`, same `moveToThread` + cancel pattern): (1) generate a valid N×N Latin square via backtracking (row+column uniqueness only, box peer cache excluded); (2) partition into cages via `KenKenCagePartitioner(size, seed, rng)` — seeded flood-fill, difficulty-controlled cage-size distribution (Easy avg 2–3 cells; Medium avg 3–4; Hard/Expert avg 4–5); individual cage size has **no explicit cap** — flood-fill is governed purely by the difficulty-average distribution target; very large cages are rare and handled gracefully by the `_KenKenCage` arithmetic feasibility pruner (R15 Q5, Option C); single-cell cage count governed by the scaled `_DIFFICULTY_GIVENS` formula: `floor(DIFFICULTY_GIVENS[difficulty] × N² / 81)` — proportionally matching the Standard/1-25 scaling; `_KENKEN_SINGLE_CELL_COUNTS` is dropped (R14 Q8, Option C); enforcement is target-based with retry: after flood-fill, if the actual single-cell count is outside the scaled target, the worker retries with `seed + 1` up to `_MAX_GENERATION_RETRIES`; the `_stop` guard prevents retrying after cancellation (R14 Q6, Option B); on exhaustion the worker emits `failed(reason: str)` and `NewGameDialog` shows an error toast ("Generation failed — please try again") and re-enables the Confirm button (R15 Q2, Option A); (3) assign operation per cage: 2-cell cages prefer `÷` if values divide exactly, else `−`; multi-cell cages prefer `×` if product is in range, else `+`; single-cell — no operation; (4) compute targets from solution; (5) remove all digits leaving cage boundaries, operations, and targets; (6) verify uniqueness via `check_unique(meta, board_state, constraint_ok=cage_arithmetic_callback, cancel_flag=cancel_flag)` — same `constraint_ok` mechanism as Killer (R11 Q9, Option A; R12 Q2, Option B); **`KenKenWorker` performs the entire generation pipeline** (steps 1–6) on the background thread and emits `finished(meta)` with a fully-generated puzzle; `GameController.new_game` receives complete meta and does not call `generate_puzzle`. (R11 Q8, Option A) Each phase seeds independently as `random.Random(seed)` — same seed value, fresh instance per phase; no state threading between Latin-square fill, cage partitioning, and uniqueness check. (R13 Q2, Option B)
- **`KenKenCagePartitioner`** in `solver/variant_generators.py`: signature `KenKenCagePartitioner(size: int, seed: int, rng: random.Random)`; `.partition(solution: list[list[int]]) -> list[dict]`; accepts optional `cancel_flag`. The `rng` parameter is accepted for interface symmetry but `KenKenCagePartitioner` creates its own `random.Random(seed)` internally for all random choices inside the partitioner; the passed `rng` is not used. (R14 Q5, Option B)
- **`is_fixed` semantics**: single-cell cages are `is_fixed = True` (target = value, acts as a given clue); all other cells start `is_fixed = False`.
- **Solver/validator**: backtracking with row/column uniqueness (no box units); cage-feasibility pruning at each placement; `validate()` checks row/column uniqueness and cage arithmetic; `GameController.is_complete` additionally verifies all cage targets satisfied (inline check, same pattern as Killer).
- **SE grader**: `_KenKenCage` technique (weight 1.9): per-cage candidate restriction using operation-specific feasibility — `+` and `×` use sum/product feasibility analogous to `_KillerCage`; `−` eliminates candidate `v` from a 2-cell cage cell when no value `w` in the paired cell satisfies `|v − w| = target`; `÷` similarly for quotient; permutation cap 10 000 (same as Killer); fires only when `meta.name == Variant.KENKEN`.
- **Persistence**: JSON includes `"variant": "kenken"`, `meta.size`, and `meta.constraints["cages"]` with `"op"` fields; stored in `constraints` dict; no schema version bump.
- **UI — cage rendering**: reuses `_draw_edges` from Killer; cage boundaries drawn with the same thick pen as box borders; cage label in topmost-leftmost cell (row-major minimum) shows operation and target: `"12+"`, `"6×"`, `"2÷"`, `"3−"` (or just the digit for single-cell given cages); label at ~20–25% cell height; pencil marks shift down/right to avoid overlap (same as Killer, R6 Q7 pattern).
- **UI — cage member highlight**: same `cage_member_bg` tint as Killer; `selected > conflict > peer > cage_member > fixed > base` priority chain.
- **UI — conflict highlighting**: flags row/column duplicates and cage cells whose partial arithmetic is provably violated (partial product/sum exceeds or cannot reach target given remaining candidates); the cage-arithmetic conflict check is performed **inside `_all_conflict_cells`** — after the row/col scan for `Variant.KENKEN`, a second pass iterates `meta.constraints["cages"]` and adds violating cage cells to the return set; one function, one call site. (R13 Q3, Option A)
- **Import/export**: text header `"variant: kenken"`, `"size: N"`; each cage on a separate `cage:` header line using the repeating-field convention: `cage: r1c1,r2c2,...:op:target` (one `cage:` line per cage) (R12 Q8, Option A); digit rows standard (`0` = empty).

### Kakuro
- **Grid**: variable-size crossword-style grid enclosed in an N×N bounding box (typical N ∈ {9, 12, 16}); cells are either **black** (header/wall) or **white** (fillable 1–9); black cells adjacent to white runs carry **clue numbers** (one across clue and/or one down clue per black cell).
- **Constraints**: each **run** (maximal consecutive sequence of white cells in one row or column bounded by black cells or the grid edge) must: (a) sum exactly to the adjacent clue; (b) contain distinct digits 1–9 within the run (no repeats per run); minimum run length ≥ 2 (single-white-cell runs are disallowed by design). **No global row/column uniqueness** — the same digit may appear in multiple runs within the same row or column.
- **`Variant` enum value**: `Variant.KAKURO = "kakuro"`.
- **Metadata**: `meta.constraints["clues"]` = list of `{"run_cells": [[r,c],...], "sum": N, "dir": "across"|"down"}` dicts; `meta.constraints["black_cells"]` = list of `[r,c]` pairs (reuses same field name as Str8ts for consistency); `meta.constraints["clue_positions"]` = list of `{"row": r, "col": c, "across": N_or_null, "down": N_or_null}` for each clue-bearing black cell — this field is **derived** at puzzle initialisation from `clues` (computed in `KakuroWorker.finished` and rebuilt from the persisted `clues` on load); it is **not** written to save files (R11 Q11, Option C); `meta.size` = bounding-box dimension N.
- **Generator** (runs on `KakuroWorker`, same `moveToThread` + cancel pattern): (1) generate a grid template via `KakuroTemplateLibrary` — the `seed` seeds the constraint-based grid builder directly and deterministically, producing exactly one layout per seed; difficulty selects the generation parameters (grid density targets and run-length target ranges); generated shapes whose white-cell proportion falls outside the difficulty-tier density band (Easy 50–65 %, Medium 40–55 %, Hard 30–45 %, Expert 25–40 %) are rejected and the builder retries with `seed + 1` up to `_MAX_GENERATION_RETRIES`; on exhaustion the worker emits `failed(reason: str)` and `NewGameDialog` shows an error toast ("Generation failed — please try again") and re-enables the Confirm button (R15 Q2, Option A; R15 Q6, Option A; R15 Q8, Option B); the `pool_size` modulo-selection design from earlier rounds is dropped (R13 Q4, Option C; R14 Q3, Option C; R14 Q4, Option C); validity additionally requires every run ≥ 2 cells (minimum run length constraint) and the full white-cell component to be a single connected region — isolated white islands are rejected; templates are runtime-generated with no pre-committed JSON files, no `importlib.resources`, no `pyproject.toml` package-data declarations required; (2) fill white cells via `KakuroFillGenerator(template, seed, rng)` — `KakuroWorker` creates `rng = random.Random(seed + N)` using the retry-adjusted seed before constructing the fill generator so template and fill are seeded consistently; `KakuroFillGenerator` uses the **passed `rng`** directly for any random tie-breaking during backtracking (R15 Q7, Option A); passes a tightest-run-first sorted `cell_order` to `_fill_grid` so backtracking visits the most-constrained runs first (R10 Q1, Option C); sum + no-repeat-per-run pruning applied at each placement; (3) expose clue numbers in black-cell headers — no white-cell digits are pre-filled (the puzzle "given" is grid shape + clue numbers only); (4) verify unique solution via `check_unique(meta, filled_board, constraint_ok=validate_kakuro, cancel_flag=cancel_flag)` (R12 Q2, Option B; R10 Q4, Option C). `KakuroTemplateLibrary` and `KakuroFillGenerator` are co-located in `solver/variant_generators.py`; both accept optional `cancel_flag`. `validate_kakuro` is also co-located in `solver/variant_generators.py` — imported by `generator.py` when building the `constraint_ok` callback for Kakuro uniqueness checks; this keeps all Kakuro-specific generator logic in one module. (R13 Q5, Option A)
- **Solver/validator**: backtracking constrained by each run's sum and no-repeat rule; `validate()` checks all run sums and intra-run digit uniqueness; does **not** check row/column global uniqueness; `GameController.is_complete` verifies all runs fully filled and sums satisfied (inline check, same pattern as Killer/KenKen).
- **SE grader**: `_KakuroRun` technique (weight 2.1): for each run, restrict per-cell candidates using run-sum feasibility + digits already placed in the same run (analogous in structure to `_Str8tsRun` but uses sum arithmetic rather than consecutive-run constraints); fires only when `meta.name == Variant.KAKURO`; no permutation cap needed for typical run lengths ≤ 9. `_WorkingGrid.__init__` detects `meta.name == Variant.KAKURO` and builds run-based units from `meta.constraints["clues"]` run cell lists instead of calling `_build_unit_groups`; standard techniques (Hidden Single, Naked Pair) apply within run-units producing correct intra-run eliminations; multi-unit fish techniques never fire because the run-unit set does not produce the cross-unit structure they require. (R10 Q3, Option A) Additionally, `_WorkingGrid.__init__` performs a Kakuro-specific pre-seeding step after building run-based units: one full pass of run-sum + no-repeat restriction across all runs is applied before the main technique loop via a shared private function `_apply_kakuro_run_restriction(grid: _WorkingGrid) -> bool` — return value follows the standard technique `_apply` convention: `True` when at least one candidate was narrowed (progress; the technique loop restarts from the top), `False` when no candidate changed (R14 Q1, Option A); `_KakuroRun._apply` delegates to this same function, and `_WorkingGrid.__init__` calls it directly without constructing a full technique object; pre-narrowed candidates give subsequent Hidden Single and Naked Pair invocations richer input. (R12 Q3, Option B; R13 Q8, Option B)
- **Persistence**: JSON includes `"variant": "kakuro"`, `meta.constraints["black_cells"]`, and `meta.constraints["clues"]`; `clue_positions` is **not** persisted — it is derived from `clues` at load time (R11 Q11, Option C); stored in `constraints` dict; no schema version bump.
- **UI — black cells**: rendered with `black_cell_bg` (same as Str8ts); clue-bearing black cells display one or two clue numbers in a **diagonal split** (standard Kakuro convention): down clue in the top-left area and across clue in the bottom-right area, separated by a diagonal line rendered in `cage_label_color`; `_draw_board` handles this as a special rendering branch for black cells carrying clue data.
- **UI — run peer highlight**: selecting any white Kakuro cell highlights all cells in its across-run **and** down-run with `peer_bg` tint (both runs together, extending the existing Str8ts black-cell peer pattern to run-based grouping).
- **UI — navigation**: arrow-key navigation and Tab/Shift-Tab skip black cells (reuses existing `_move_selection` and `_advance_selection` skip-black logic from Str8ts).
- **UI — conflict highlighting**: flags cells in a run whose partial-sum state exceeds the clue target or cannot be reached given remaining candidates; flags duplicate digits within a run.
- **Import/export**: text header `"variant: kakuro"`, `"size: N"`, `"black_cells"` as compact row strings (`.`/`B` per row joined by `/`); each clue on a separate `clue:` header line using the repeating-field convention: `clue: r1c1,r1c2,...:sum:dir` (one `clue:` line per run) (R12 Q8, Option A); digit rows use `0` for empty whites and `_` for black cells.

## Milestones
- MVP (aligns with roadmap): standard 9x9 UI, generation, validate, save/load JSON, timer, pencil marks, undo/redo, basic themes (light/dark, Arial), keyboard-only paths.
- Beta: add Jigsaw, Str8ts, Killer; hints (multi-mode), conflict highlighting, import/export, difficulty selection, move/hint tracking, end-of-game stats. The 1–25, Codewords, KenKen, and Kakuro options are **present but greyed out** in `NewGameDialog` — each becomes active individually as its Extended Variant implementation batch is completed.
- Extended Variants: enable `ONE_TO_25` (25×25, 5×5 box regions, `OneToTwentyFiveWorker`, auto-scaling UI); add `CODEWORDS` (`CodewordsWorker`, letter display, Codebook Panel, `_CodewordsMapping` SE technique weight 1.3); add `KENKEN` (`KenKenCagePartitioner`, `KenKenWorker`, arithmetic operations +/−/×/÷, `_KenKenCage` SE technique weight 1.9); add `KAKURO` (`KakuroTemplateLibrary`, `KakuroFillGenerator`, `KakuroWorker`, diagonal clue labels, `_KakuroRun` SE technique weight 2.1). All four integrate via the existing variant registry, background-worker, `_draw_edges`, and persistence patterns established in Beta.
- Full: puzzle editor, online sharing, multiplayer timed challenges, cloud saves, mobile-friendly UI, further solver optimization, advanced SE techniques (XY-Wing, XYZ-Wing, Unique Rectangles, BUG, Forcing Chains).

## Acceptance Criteria (per PRD/Checklist)
- Users can start, play, and finish standard Sudoku with responsive UI and preserved state on save/load.
- Variants playable with consistent controls and assistance; import/export loads solvable puzzles and remains playable end-to-end.
- Statistics (time, moves, hints) tracked and shown at completion; hint limits enforceable; keyboard-only flows supported.
- Architecture remains modular with typed interfaces and validated inputs; persistence is versioned and backward compatible.
- Meets performance budgets and passes test suite outlined above.
